goals.question: What is the relationship between life expectancy and income?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of life expectancy vs income
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there is a correlation between income and life expectancy. It will also help us identify any outliers or patterns in the data.

goals.question: What is the distribution of income across different countries?
goals.visualization: Box plot of income by country
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the range, median, and outliers of income across different countries. It will also help us identify any countries with significantly higher or lower income levels.

goals.question: What is the trend of child mortality rate over time?
goals.visualization: Line chart of child mortality rate over time
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if child mortality rate has been decreasing over time. It will also help us identify any significant changes or patterns in the trend.

goals.question: What is the distribution of population across different regions?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of population by region
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the relative size of population across different regions. It will also help us identify any regions with significantly higher or lower population levels.

goals.question: What is the relationship between education and income?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of education vs income
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there is a correlation between education and income. It will also help us identify any outliers or patterns in the data.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.scatter(data['income'], data['life_expectancy'])
    plt.xlabel('Income')
    plt.ylabel('Life Expectancy')
    plt.title('What is the relationship between life expectancy and income?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    data.boxplot(column='income', by='country', ax=ax)
    ax.set_title('What is the distribution of income across different countries?')
    ax.set_xlabel('Country')
    ax.set_ylabel('Income')
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.legend(title='Income')
    plt.tight_layout()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['year'])]
    
    plt.plot(data['year'], data['child_mortality_rate'], label='Child Mortality Rate')
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel('Child Mortality Rate')
    plt.title('What is the trend of child mortality rate over time?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    # Group data by region and sum the population
    grouped_data = data.groupby('region')['population'].sum().reset_index()

    # Create a bar chart
    plt.bar(grouped_data['region'], grouped_data['population'])

    # Set chart title and labels
    plt.title('What is the distribution of population across different regions?')
    plt.xlabel('Region')
    plt.ylabel('Population')

    # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)

    # Add legend
    plt.legend(['Population'])

    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
